---

<Infographic
  title="What the quantum internet is for"
  description="The applications that consume Bell pairs as a network resource: QKD, distributed quantum computing, blind quantum computing, networked sensing, and clock synchronisation. Each places different demands on the network's entanglement-delivery rate, fidelity, and reach."
  references={[
    "cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "wehner-science-2018",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="applications" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>What the quantum internet is for</h1>
        <p>
          A quantum network's product is delivered Bell pairs. The applications consume
          them: cryptographic key extraction, teleportation between processors, blind
          delegation, distributed sensing, and synchronised clocks. Different applications
          place different demands on the network's entanglement-delivery rate, fidelity,
          and reach — and the maturity ladder is steep. Today's deployed application is
          QKD; the rest are in research or pilot
          stages <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Wehner et al. 2018 organised the application landscape as a five-stage roadmap
          tied to network capability: trusted-node QKD → prepare-and-measure QKD →
          entanglement distribution → quantum memory → fault-tolerant. Each stage unlocks
          its corresponding application class <SourceNote id="wehner-science-2018" />.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="qkd" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Quantum key distribution (QKD)</h2>
        <p>
          QKD is the only application of quantum networking with commercial deployment
          today. Two paradigm families: <strong>prepare-and-measure</strong> protocols
          (BB84 and its variants, with decoy states for security against
          photon-number-splitting attacks) where Alice prepares states and Bob measures;
          and <strong>entanglement-based</strong> protocols (BBM92, Ekert91) where a
          shared Bell pair is the resource. Variants address specific operational
          constraints: <strong>Measurement-Device-Independent QKD</strong> (MDI-QKD) puts
          the trust in the source and removes detector side-channel attacks;
          <strong>Twin-Field QKD</strong> (TF-QKD) scales the key rate as √η rather than
          η, doubling effective reach.
        </p>
        <p>
          QKD requires the lowest fidelity threshold of any quantum-network application —
          ~0.85 raw is workable after error correction and privacy amplification, and
          field-deployed systems run reliably between metropolitan-scale endpoints. The
          bulk of vendor activity in quantum networking is QKD <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="dqc" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Distributed quantum computing (DQC)</h2>
        <p>
          A single quantum processor with a fixed qubit count is bounded by what its
          chip-scale platform allows; networking processors into a cluster lets the
          combined machine run circuits larger than any single node. The networking
          primitive is <strong>gate teleportation</strong>: a CNOT between qubits at two
          different nodes is performed by consuming a Bell pair and exchanging a small
          number of classical bits. The protocol generalises to other two-qubit gates
          and to higher-fidelity primitives via distillation.
        </p>
        <p>
          DQC's demands on the network are strict: gate teleportation requires fidelities
          above ~0.99 to compose into a useful multi-gate circuit. The end-to-end
          fidelity drops multiplicatively with depth, so DQC sits at the high-fidelity
          end of the application spectrum and depends critically on
          distillation <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="bqc" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Blind quantum computing (BQC)</h2>
        <p>
          A client has sensitive input data and wants a remote quantum server to compute
          on it without learning the inputs or outputs. <strong>Blind quantum computing</strong>
          protocols achieve this: the client prepares (or has delivered) qubits in known
          states known only to them, sends them to the server, and the server executes
          the computation through measurement-based protocols on those qubits. Because
          the server never learns the state encoding, it learns nothing about the data.
        </p>
        <p>
          BQC is appealing for high-value privacy use cases — financial computations,
          pharmaceutical search, government applications. Like DQC it requires high
          fidelity and is currently research-stage.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="sensing" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Networked sensing & clock synchronisation</h2>
        <p>
          Entanglement between sensors at different locations improves measurement
          precision beyond what classical correlation allows. Two well-developed
          applications:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Networked atomic clocks.</strong> Distributing entangled states
            between geographically separated atomic clocks lets the network's frequency
            measurement scale better than √N with the number of clocks (Heisenberg-limited
            rather than shot-noise-limited).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Distributed interferometry.</strong> Very-long-baseline
            interferometry (VLBI) for astronomy can in principle use entangled photon
            pairs to extend the effective baseline. This is research-level but
            theoretically promising.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Sensing applications consume entanglement differently from QKD or DQC — the
          fidelity threshold can be more relaxed in some protocols, but the
          source-of-randomness and timing-precision constraints are
          tighter <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="demands" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Cross-application demands</h2>
        <p>
          The four application families have qualitatively different requirements on
          rate, fidelity, and reach:
        </p>

        <table class="apps-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Application</th>
              <th scope="col">Rate</th>
              <th scope="col">Fidelity</th>
              <th scope="col">Reach</th>
              <th scope="col">Deployment</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">QKD</th>
              <td>kbit/s–Mbit/s key rates</td>
              <td>Modest (~0.85 raw)</td>
              <td>Metro to satellite</td>
              <td>Commercial, fielded</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Distributed QC</th>
              <td>Per-gate Bell pairs</td>
              <td>High (≥0.99)</td>
              <td>Datacentre to metro</td>
              <td>Research / early proto</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Blind QC</th>
              <td>Per-computation</td>
              <td>High (≥0.99)</td>
              <td>Client-to-server, any</td>
              <td>Research</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Networked sensing</th>
              <td>Application-specific</td>
              <td>Protocol-specific</td>
              <td>City to global</td>
              <td>Research</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p>
          The metrics subject covers what these demands mean for a network's engineering
          budget; the maturity subject covers where each application sits on the TRL
          ladder <SourceNote id="cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020" />.
        </p>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

